---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "agents-api")!;

const curlExample = `curl https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages \\
  --header "x-api-key: $ANTHROPIC_API_KEY" \\
  --header "anthropic-version: 2023-06-01" \\
  --header "content-type: application/json" \\
  --data '{
    "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
    "max_tokens": 256,
    "messages": [
      {"role": "user", "content": "Say hello in one sentence."}
    ]
  }'`;

const pythonExample = `pip install anthropic

from anthropic import Anthropic
client = Anthropic()  # reads ANTHROPIC_API_KEY from env

reply = client.messages.create(
    model="claude-sonnet-4-6",
    max_tokens=256,
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Say hello in one sentence."}],
)
print(reply.content[0].text)`;

const tsExample = `npm install @anthropic-ai/sdk

import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";
const client = new Anthropic(); // reads ANTHROPIC_API_KEY from env

const reply = await client.messages.create({
  model: "claude-sonnet-4-6",
  max_tokens: 256,
  messages: [{ role: "user", content: "Say hello in one sentence." }],
});
console.log((reply.content[0] as any).text);`;

const codeBlockStyle =
  "background: #1c1916; color: #e8dec8; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 12px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.82rem; overflow: auto; line-height: 1.5;";
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        The <strong>Claude API</strong> is what lets <em>any</em> tool talk to Claude — Anthropic's
        own apps, every open-source agent, and any side project you might build. Once you understand
        the shape of it, every other tool's "set up Claude" instructions become trivial.
      </p>

      <h2>The three things you need</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li><strong>An API key.</strong> A long string starting with <code class="inline">sk-ant-</code>. You get one from <a href="https://console.anthropic.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">console.anthropic.com</a> after adding a payment method.</li>
        <li><strong>A model name.</strong> Like <code class="inline">claude-sonnet-4-6</code> or <code class="inline">claude-opus-4-7</code>. Tells the API which Claude to use.</li>
        <li><strong>A request.</strong> Send your prompt, get a response. That's it.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>One call, in three languages</h2>

      <h3>Bash (curl)</h3>
      <pre style={codeBlockStyle}>{curlExample}</pre>

      <h3>Python (with the SDK)</h3>
      <pre style={codeBlockStyle}>{pythonExample}</pre>

      <h3>TypeScript (with the SDK)</h3>
      <pre style={codeBlockStyle}>{tsExample}</pre>

      <h2>The shape of every "set up Claude in tool X"</h2>
      <p>Once you've seen one, you've seen them all. Every open-source agent's setup boils down to:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Get an <code class="inline">sk-ant-…</code> key.</li>
        <li>Tell the tool about it — usually an <code class="inline">ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code> env var, sometimes a file like <code class="inline">~/.hermes/.env</code> or a CLI prompt.</li>
        <li>Optionally pick a model.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>That's the whole game. Hermes? Same three steps. OpenClaw? Same three steps. Aider? Same three steps.</p>

      <h2>Models worth knowing</h2>
      <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 0.6rem 0; font-size: 0.92rem;">
        <thead>
          <tr style="background: var(--surface-2);">
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Model</th>
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">When to use</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><code class="inline">claude-haiku-4-5</code></td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Fastest + cheapest. Routine tasks, classification, simple lookups.</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><code class="inline">claude-sonnet-4-6</code></td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Default. Best balance for code, writing, agents.</td></tr>
          <tr><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);"><code class="inline">claude-opus-4-7</code></td><td style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--line);">Heaviest reasoning. Architecture, research, gnarly debugging.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Prompt caching.</strong> When a tool sends the same context (system prompt, project files, history) repeatedly,
        Anthropic can <em>cache</em> the input — drastically cheaper and faster. Good tools (Claude Code, Hermes, aider) do this automatically.
      </div>

      <Reveal q="Do I need a paid Anthropic account to use these tools?">
        Yes. Free Claude.ai uses Anthropic's apps; running open-source agents requires an API key, which requires a payment method.
        Start with a small spend cap.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Can I keep my key safe?">
        Never commit it to git. Put it in an env file (<code class="inline">.env</code>) that's git-ignored, or your OS keychain.
        Rotate immediately if it's ever exposed.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
